    <h3><a name="4"></a>Nov 10 (2 posts): <a href="http://docs.FreeBSD.org/cgi/getmsg.cgi?fetch=92969+0+archive/2000/freebsd-advocacy/20001112.freebsd-advocacy">FreeBSD Foundation: Examples of FreeBSD as teaching aid/research platform</a></h3>

    <p><a href="mailto:keichii@iteration.net">[Michael Wu]</a> sends us a
      couple specific examples of how FreeBSD is used as either a teaching
      aid or a research platform by educational institutions.</p>

    <ul>
      <li><a href="http://www.csie.nctu.edu.tw/os">National Chiao Tung
	University</A> - The Department of Computer Science and
	Information Engineering at this university in Taiwan uses FreeBSD
	to teach OS Arch.  An estimated 10-15% of *.edu.tw workstations
	are running FreeBSD, with a major following in the dorms as well.</li>

      <li><a href="http://ece.utexas.edu">University of Texas at Austin</a> 
	- As a teaching assistant, Michael himself uses FreeBSD as a
	supplement his classes.  The Professor uses C++, Codewarrior/x86,
	and he has decided to withhold opinion on that.</li>

      <li><a href="http://physics.purdue.edu">Purdue</a> - runs FreeBSD
	in their computer labs, according to <a
	href="mailto:will@FreeBSD.org">Will Andrews]</a>.</li>

      <li><a href="http://www.usc.edu/dept/engineering/infotech/ITP%20499%20Unix%20System%20Administration.htm">University
	of Southern California</a> - has a course on FreeBSD System
	Administration, but <a href="mailto:kris@FreeBSD.org">[Kris
	Kennaway]</a> isn't sure on how often its offered.  "The Complete
	FreeBSD" by Greg Lehey is required material.</li>
    </ul>

